{"id":14881742,"mediaExerciseId":"a423bdcd-2eca-4c24-a7f8-3d3415ea5ad4","exerciseName":"22","chapterName":"20","chapterTitle":"Credit and Inventory Management","groupId":612459,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":703,"solutions":[{"id":6411224,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will introduce the concept of default in a credit policy.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A default means that the credit policy was not paid by the customer. This means that the company loses value from it. In order to determine whether the company should still offer credit policy despite the $15\\%$ default rate, we can use this formula:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Net present value}&=(1-0.15)\\times\\text{Cash flow}-\\text{Costs}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nFrom the previous problem, we can get the total cash flow as $\\$790,758.48$ and the costs are $\\$862,500$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Substituting the values from the previous problem, we will get:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Net present value}&=(1-0.15)\\times\\$790,758.48-\\$862,500\\\\[15 pt]\n&=-\\$190,355.29\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nThis shows that the net present value is negative which means that the company should not extend credit policies. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"81f871bd-056a-4e6e-8bb3-b970eb8ff84f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumb